<Document>
<name>Cordillera — Baguio to Sagada to Banaue</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Cordillera — Baguio to Sagada to Banaue</h2><p><i>Luzon, Philippines · Cordillera Central, Baguio to Banaue via Bontoc</i></p><p><b>Mountain Province highlands — 2,000-year-old rice terraces, hanging coffins, pine-clad ridges.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>128 km (79 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>2 days minimum</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>December–May (drier); July–October typhoon season can close mountain roads</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Steep, twisting, often narrow road; landslides in rain; typhoon-season closures; thin shoulders, blind hairpins; bus traffic</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>326</td></tr></table><hr><p>The Cordillera Central is Luzon's spine — a high range (peaks above 2,800 m) where the Igorot peoples (Bontoc, Ifugao, Kankanaey, Kalinga, and others) maintained their independence through 350 years of Spanish colonial rule. The Banaue and Batad rice terraces, carved into impossibly steep slopes around 2,000 years ago, are UNESCO World Heritage and one of the great engineering achievements of pre-industrial humanity. Sagada is the cultural-tourism stop on the way — pine-forest cool air, hanging coffins suspended on cliffs (a continuing Sagada tradition), and the Sumaguing limestone caves. The road from Baguio to Banaue (the 'Halsema Highway' from Baguio to Bontoc, then onward) is 200 km that takes 8+ hours — narrow, twisting, periodically buried by landslide. Worth every minute.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Baguio</b> — Summer capital of the Philippines (1,400 m). Built 1900s by the American colonial government as a hill station. Burnham Park, Session Road; cool weather; Igorot crafts at the Maharlika and Easter Weaving School.</li><li><b>Atok / Halsema highway</b> — The road's high point at ~2,255 m — once the highest road in the Philippines. Vegetable terraces stair-step down both sides; cabbages, lettuce, broccoli. Strawberries (and strawberry taho — silken tofu in syrup) sold at Mount Pulag turnoff.</li><li><b>Sagada</b> — Pine-forest village famous for hanging coffins still installed by the Kankanaey on cliffs at Echo Valley. Sumaguing cave (helmets, headlamps, guides) is a strenuous 2-hour wade through underground rivers.</li><li><b>Bontoc</b> — Provincial capital. Bontoc Museum is a hidden gem — old photographs of headhunting expeditions, original textiles, a reconstructed traditional Bontoc village in the courtyard.</li><li><b>Banaue</b> — Main viewpoint town for the rice terraces — but the most-photographed terraces (the 'amphitheater') are at Batad, 12 km on. Banaue town itself is a strung-out highway settlement; sleep at Batad if you can.</li><li><b>Batad rice terraces</b> — Amphitheater of stone-walled terraces around a small village reachable only on foot from the road end. Walk down through the terraces, stay overnight in a homestay, hike out to the Tappiya waterfall (1 hr down). UNESCO World Heritage.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
